04779nam a22006855i 9780691186207DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911862077 a10.1515/97806911862072doi  a(DE-B1597)501580  a(OCoLC)1076457528  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aML1711b.K6 2005eb 7aMUS0460002bisacsh04a782.1/4/09732221 aKnapp, Raymond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Musical and the Formation of National Identity /cRaymond Knapp. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tExplanatory Note about Audio Examples -- tPreface -- tPart One. INTRODUCTIONS -- t1. Contexts and Strategies -- t2. Nineteenth-Century European Roots: Models and Topics -- t3. Early American Developments: Minstrelsy, Extravaganza, Pantomime, Burlesque, Vaudeville -- t4. American Song through Tin Pan Alley -- tPart Two. DEFINING AMERICA -- t5. Whose (Who's) America? -- t6. American Mythologies -- t7. Counter-mythologies -- tPart Three. MANAGING AMERICA'S OTHERS -- t8. Race and Ethnicity -- t9. Dealing with the Second World War -- t10. Exoticism -- t11. Afterword: Other Directions, Other Identities -- tAppendix A. Art and Commerce: The Business of Making Musicals -- tAppendix B. Additional Resources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe American musical has achieved and maintained relevance to more people in America than any other performance-based art. This thoughtful history of the genre, intended for readers of all stripes, offers probing discussions of how American musicals, especially through their musical numbers, advance themes related to American national identity. Written by a musicologist and supported by a wealth of illustrative audio examples (on the book's website), the book examines key historical antecedents to the musical, including the Gilbert and Sullivan operetta, nineteenth and early twentieth-century American burlesque and vaudeville, Tin Pan Alley, and other song types. It then proceeds thematically, focusing primarily on fifteen mainstream shows from the twentieth century, with discussions of such notable productions as Show Boat (1927), Porgy and Bess (1935), Oklahoma! (1943), West Side Story (1957), Hair (1967), Pacific Overtures (1976), and Assassins (1991). The shows are grouped according to their treatment of themes that include defining America, mythologies, counter-mythologies, race and ethnicity, dealing with World War II, and exoticism. Each chapter concludes with a brief consideration of available scholarship on related subjects; an extensive appendix provides information on each show discussed, including plot summaries and song lists, and a listing of important films, videos, audio recordings, published scores, and libretti associated with each musical.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMusicalszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aNational characteristics, American. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Musicals.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691186207zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691186207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691186207.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_S